    {
      "file": "./models.ts",
      "description": "Get to know your data!\r\n\r\nHere we have alarms and user events data.\r\nYou will need to help process this information\r\n\r\nScroll down this page and view the user events.\r\nTake note of the structure - location, names, severity and everything",
      "line": 1,
      "title": "Know your data"
    },
    {
      "file": "Completions.ts",
      "description": "Using GHCP completions is optimal for Short, Specific and Simple logic (The 3 `S` principle), remember that!\r\n\r\n\r\nFor best completions results - \r\nName a variable according to the logic you expect and then refactor the name after.\r\n\r\nPro tips:\r\n1. GHCP also suggests names (!) if you press Refactor (F2) on the function/variable name.\r\n2. Watch this for more context on [The 3 `S` Principal](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hh1nOX14TyY&t=38s&ab_channel=VisualStudioCode)",
      "line": 1,
      "title": "Completions introduction"
    },
    {
      "file": "./Completions.ts",
      "description": "#1 Let's warm up and let Copilot do it for us, please create a variable to store the total alarm events.\r\n\r\nSimply place your caret after the equal sign and hit space.\r\nLet's see what GC completes.",
      "line": 2,
      "title": "Completions #1"
    },
    {
      "file": "./Completions.ts",
      "description": "#2 Your first attempt at solo assignment, save the number of user events into a variable.\r\n\r\nHowever, look! Github Copilot knows exactly what to do, and offers you to create exactly that variable on your behalf!",
      "line": 5,
      "title": "Completions #2"
    },
    {
      "file": "./Completions.ts",
      "description": "#3 So for your actual solo assignment - create a variable to store the total number of events, user and alarms.",
      "line": 8,
      "title": "Completions #3"
    },
    {
      "file": "./Completions.ts",
      "description": "#4 Create a method to count the total alarm events which happened by an input of location",
      "line": 11,
      "title": "Completions #4"
    },
    {
      "file": "./Completions.ts",
      "description": "#5 Find the list of users names which were at the same location where the alarm events occurred.\r\nDo not input any parameters and let Copilot iterate over the data and find the matching pairs.\r\n\r\nShould return an array of user *names*, example: [\"Brad\", \"Lee\", \"Cooper\"]",
      "line": 14,
      "title": "Completions #5"
    },
    {
      "file": "./Completions.ts",
      "description": "#6 Create a dictionary with keys of alarm severities and a count of how many alarm events of respective severity type events occurred.\r\n\r\nExample output:\r\n{ \r\n    Low: 2,\r\n    Medium: 3,\r\n    High: 3\r\n}",
      "line": 17,
      "title": "Completions #6"
    },
    {
      "file": "../GHCP-Typescript.code-workspace",
      "description": "# 🆕 From Prompt Engineering to Context Engineering\r\n\r\n## The New Standard: AGENTS.md\r\n\r\nVS Code now supports **two formats** for repository-wide custom instructions:\r\n\r\n1. **AGENTS.md** (NEW - recommended format)\r\n   - Place at the root of your workspace\r\n   - Now **generally available** and enabled by default\r\n   - Supports **nested AGENTS.md files** in subfolders (experimental via `chat.useNestedAgentsMdFiles` setting)\r\n   - Provide context-specific instructions for different parts of your codebase (e.g., frontend vs backend)\r\n\r\n2. **.github/copilot-instructions.md** (legacy format)\r\n   - Still supported for backward compatibility\r\n   - Consider migrating to AGENTS.md for better support\r\n\r\n## Context Engineering in Practice\r\n\r\n### Utilize VS Code workspaces\r\n\r\n1. Setup your Copilot instructions for test creation, code generation, code-reviews and even commit messages.\r\n2. Commit the VS Code workspace in your repo and instruct your team to use it for development.\r\n3. Instructions come in the form of free text in markdown files. The more context you enrich Github Copilot with, the better results you'll get.\r\n\r\n### Nested AGENTS.md Example\r\n```\r\nproject-root/\r\n├── AGENTS.md              # General project guidelines\r\n├── frontend/\r\n│   └── AGENTS.md          # Frontend-specific instructions\r\n└── backend/\r\n    └── AGENTS.md          # Backend-specific instructions\r\n```\r\n\r\n**Pro Tip:** The more contextual and specific your instructions, the better Copilot performs. This is why we call it **Context Engineering** over Prompt Engineering!\r\n\r\nSee [docs](https://docs.github.com/en/copilot/how-tos/configure-custom-instructions/add-repository-instructions#creating-repository-wide-custom-instructions)",
      "pattern": "github.copilot.chat.commitMessageGeneration.instructions",
      "title": "🆕 Context Engineering with AGENTS.md"
    },
    {
      "file": "InlineChat.ts",
      "description": "Using GHCP Inline Chat fits scenarios where you need more than one thing at a time, a very specific logic that's too long for a variable name, or you want to provide examples (yes, that's a recommendation!).\r\n\r\nIn VS Code the default shortcut is ctrl + I to open inline chat.\r\n\r\nDoes the below code work? If not, try selecting the function, and prompt inline chat again with `/fix`.\r\n\r\nLazy tip:\r\nIf the thought of typing a lot is what deters you, consider talking to VS Code! Using the extension \"VS Code Speech\" (Also recommended in workspace and should be installed) you can simply talk to VS Code with speech to text.",
      "line": 72,
      "title": "Inline chat introduction"
    },
    {
      "file": "./InlineChat.ts",
      "description": "Create a method which returns a list of the user's name property if the alarm and user events overlap in time (exactly).\r\nDuring the comparison, if there's a match, console log the alarm name and user name\r\n\r\nNow you're probably thinking -\r\n\r\nCan I copy and paste this? The answer is yes. But how will you practice phrasing your requirements?\r\n\r\nIf the thought of typing a lot is what deters you, consider talking to VS Code! Using the extension \"VS Code Speech\" (Also recommended in workspace and should be installed) you can simply talk to VS Code with speech to text. This works very well and can be done both in editor, in inline chat as well as in the chat window, give it a go!\r\n\r\n",
      "line": 74,
      "title": "Inline chat 1"
    },
    {
      "file": "./InlineChat.ts",
      "description": "Create method which creates a dictionary of alarm events by alarm name, unless the name contains intrusion (Casing insensitive). In the value store the event locations as a list.\r\n\r\nExample: \r\n{\r\n    'Gas Leak': ['Kitchen', 'Bathroom'],\r\n    ...\r\n}\r\n\r\n\r\nNow we have to stop for a second to ask: But why can't I simply use comments instead? They are also left in the repo explaining what the code below does!\r\n\r\n  1. Code gets refactored, comments usually do not. These comments will demand a cleanup in the future and get disregarded and become irrelevant.\r\n  2. More importantly, comments with GHCP aren't iterable, meaning it's a one-shot completions attempt. If you get it wrong, you have to edit your comment and try again. When using the inline chat you can then reply with what needs to be fixed. Just think of how rare it is when you code things that work for the first time, the better you are explaining what you want to GHCP, the better GHCP will help you, sometimes it takes a few rounds of explanations, a.k.a. \"inline chat ;)\"",
      "line": 76,
      "selection": {
        "start": {
          "line": 1,
          "character": 1
        },
        "end": {
          "line": 6,
          "character": 2
        }
      },
      "title": "Inline chat 2"
    },
    {
      "title": "🆕 Real-World Application: AI-Assisted Merge Conflict Resolution",
      "description": "# 🆕 Resolve Merge Conflicts with AI\r\n\r\n**New in VS Code 1.105**: When you open a file with git merge conflict markers, VS Code now offers AI-powered conflict resolution!\r\n\r\n## How It Works\r\n\r\n1. **Automatic Detection**: When merge conflicts are detected, a new action appears in the lower right-hand corner of the editor\r\n2. **AI Analysis**: Click the action to open the Chat view\r\n3. **Context-Aware Resolution**: The AI analyzes:\r\n   - The merge base (common ancestor)\r\n   - Changes from your current branch\r\n   - Changes from the incoming branch\r\n4. **Review & Customize**: You can review the proposed resolution and provide additional context if needed\r\n\r\n## Customization with AGENTS.md\r\n\r\nYou can customize the merge conflict resolution behavior using an `AGENTS.md` file in your repository. This allows you to:\r\n- Define team-specific merge strategies\r\n- Add project conventions for conflict resolution\r\n- Specify preferred resolution patterns\r\n\r\n## When to Use This\r\n\r\n✅ **Great for:**\r\n- Complex merge conflicts with multiple changes\r\n- Understanding what both branches were trying to accomplish\r\n- Getting suggestions when you're unsure which changes to keep\r\n\r\n⚠️ **Remember:**\r\n- Always review AI suggestions carefully\r\n- Test the resolved code before committing\r\n- You have the final say - the AI provides suggestions, not decisions\r\n\r\n**Note**: This feature explains and demonstrates what's available. During the workshop, we'll mention this exists and how to access it when you encounter merge conflicts in real projects."
    },
    {
      "file": "Chat.ts",
      "description": "Using GHCP Chat is ideal for discussions, questions and guidance and reassurance of your code. \r\nWith GCHP chat (CTRL + ALT + I), it's much easier to provide more context using ALIASES, we'll talk about aliases next.\r\nThe more context you add, the more capable Copilot would be.\r\n\r\n\r\nSome (none?) standard examples one can use:\r\n1. \"Check if I missed any edge cases in #selection\"\r\n2. \"Can you provide a numerical example?\" (If you can't remember if you should compare time)\r\n3. \"How do I run the project?\" More often than not, the instructions may be a little obscure, Copilot knows how to simplify and provide simple commands.\r\n4. Using it for some git operations! \"What command to edit the last commit message?\"\r\n\r\nRemember context is everything, if GHCP chat starts providing bad information, it may be confused with older contexts, don't ask him about C# and jump to typescript, create a new chat for these subject jumps. You can always navigate to previous sessions.\r\n",
      "line": 1,
      "title": "Chat introduction"
    },
    {
      "file": "Chat.ts",
      "description": "Before proceeding, open the panel (Again, Ctrl+Alt+I) and let's get to know our aliases \"`@`\", context accessors \"`#`\" and operations \"`/`\".\r\n\r\nStart typing each of these and see what operations show up in the pop up completion, take the time and iterate with Up and Down arrows. Read a little to know about the possibilities these provide, they are very useful.\r\n\r\nWorth noting - if you've heard of Copilot Edits (Ctrl+Shift+I, for the curious).. It's \"equivalent\" to adding specific files as context, with the change that code is being applied directly to the files in the working set (the context provided), and possibly behind the scenes it's processed differently. More on Copilot Edits at a different lab.",
      "line": 2,
      "selection": {
        "start": {
          "line": 1,
          "character": 1
        },
        "end": {
          "line": 5,
          "character": 347
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "file": "./Chat.ts",
      "description": "Open up Copilot (Ctrl + Shift + I) and make it prompt it, to get a list the `AlarmEvent` keys.\r\n\r\nCopilot should chat list out: \r\ntime,\r\n\r\nseverity,\r\n\r\nlocation,\r\n\r\nname.\r\n\r\n\r\nHint: If you can't get it work, try opening the file to provide context! As we said, context is everything! Can't find it? Consider skipping this one and coming back to it!\r\n\r\n\r\n",
      "line": 3,
      "title": "Chat 1"
    },
    {
      "file": "./Chat.ts",
      "description": "Using Copilot, ask it where you can find the `UserEvent` interface?\r\n\r\nExpected result, get a reference to `models.ts`",
      "line": 5,
      "title": "Chat 2"
    },
    {
      "file": "./Chat.ts",
      "description": "Somewhere in the code, I've listed several SECRET keys. Why don't you try and ask Copilot to list them for you? \r\nYou may use #codebase or @workspace (at the beginning) to list them, give it a try.\r\n\r\nHint: there are a couple of variations and typos, to the secret keywords. Find all isn't an option.",
      "line": 7,
      "title": "Chat 3"
    },
    {
      "file": "models.ts",
      "description": "**Copilot Edits** (Shortcut: _Ctrl+Shift+I_)\r\n\r\nUsed to **edit multiple files at the same time**! \r\n\r\nChanges are applied directly to the files provided as context / detected by Copilot, these files are also called \"working set\" and recently the 10 file limit has been removed (yay).\r\n\r\nLet's start with the prompt:\r\n\r\n\"_Add a logger to the AlarmEvent type and log the important properties_\"",
      "line": 8,
      "title": "Copilot edits 😮"
    },
    {
      "file": "models.ts",
      "description": "Introducing Agent mode, same functionality of editing multiple files, but with iterations. Let's call it edits ++ \r\n\r\nLet's ask Copilot to create the spec for our functionality:\r\n\r\n`\r\nI want the main function to use the different functions that exists in the code base. And allow the user to filter specific alarms based on inputs. So this will now be a console app that runs on the generated alarms, and while the alarms are generated every second in the background. Without interfering with alarm generation, the user will be able to get the current status by choosing a number from the menu which will execute a specific function.`\r\n\r\nBut before that, **copy the prompt above** and let's use our [special prompt](.github\\prompts\\Feature breakdown prompt.prompt.md):\r\n\r\n\r\nCtrl + Shift + P -> Use prompt\r\n\r\nPaste the prompt, and take the response.",
      "line": 8,
      "title": "Github Copilot Agent 🤯"
    },
    {
      "title": "🆕 Plan Before You Code: The Plan Agent",
      "description": "# 🆕 The Plan Agent - Your AI Planning Assistant\r\n\r\n**New in VS Code Insiders**: The built-in **Plan Agent** helps you prepare for complex coding tasks before writing a single line of code!\r\n\r\n## Why Plan First?\r\n\r\nJumping straight into code can lead to:\r\n- ❌ Missing important requirements\r\n- ❌ Overlooking edge cases\r\n- ❌ Inefficient architecture decisions\r\n- ❌ Rework and refactoring\r\n\r\nThe Plan Agent helps you **analyze tasks, break them down into steps, and generate implementation plans** before development.\r\n\r\n## How to Use the Plan Agent\r\n\r\n1. **Open Chat View**: Press `Ctrl+Alt+I`\r\n2. **Select Plan Agent**: Click the agents dropdown and select **@plan**\r\n3. **Describe Your Task**: Explain what you want to build\r\n4. **Review the Plan**: The agent will:\r\n   - Analyze requirements\r\n   - Break down into logical steps\r\n   - Identify potential challenges\r\n   - Suggest implementation approach\r\n5. **Next Steps**: You can either:\r\n   - Start implementation immediately\r\n   - Save the plan for later\r\n   - Refine the plan with follow-up questions\r\n\r\n## Example Workflow\r\n\r\n```\r\nYou: @plan Create a user authentication system with JWT tokens\r\n\r\nPlan Agent:\r\n1. Analysis of requirements\r\n2. Database schema design\r\n3. JWT token generation logic\r\n4. Authentication middleware\r\n5. Error handling strategy\r\n6. Security considerations\r\n...\r\n```\r\n\r\n## Integration with Handoffs\r\n\r\nThe Plan Agent uses the new **handoff feature** - after finalizing your plan, you'll see buttons to transition to the next mode with the plan context preserved!\r\n\r\n**Pro Tip**: Complex features benefit most from planning. Use this for:\r\n- New feature development\r\n- Architecture refactoring\r\n- Integration projects\r\n- Performance optimization tasks\r\n\r\n**Availability**: VS Code Insiders only (as of version 1.105)"
    },
    {
      "title": "🆕 🚀 SUPER IMPORTANT: Delegate Research with Subagents",
      "description": "# 🆕 Isolated Subagents - The Game Changer\r\n\r\n**New in VS Code Insiders**: **Subagents** let you delegate autonomous tasks to specialized AI agents within your chat sessions - and this is HUGE for managing context!\r\n\r\n## The Context Problem\r\n\r\nEver noticed how your chat sessions get \"bloated\" with information?\r\n- Research about different approaches\r\n- API documentation lookups\r\n- Code analysis from multiple files\r\n- All this fills up your main context window\r\n\r\n## How Subagents Solve This\r\n\r\nSubagents operate with **their own separate context window** and work **autonomously without user interaction**. They:\r\n\r\n✅ **Complete their task independently**\r\n✅ **Return results to your main chat**\r\n✅ **Keep your main context clean**\r\n✅ **Don't pollute your conversation history**\r\n\r\n## Using Subagents\r\n\r\n### In Chat Prompts\r\n```\r\nRun #runSubagent tool for context gathering and research about auth mechanisms for this app.\r\n```\r\n\r\n### In Custom Chat Modes\r\nYou can reference `#runSubagent` in your custom mode definitions to automatically delegate research tasks.\r\n\r\n### Ideal Use Cases\r\n- 🔍 **Research**: \"Investigate all authentication patterns used in #codebase\"\r\n- 📊 **Analysis**: \"Analyze performance bottlenecks across all services\"\r\n- 📚 **Context Gathering**: \"Find all error handling approaches in the project\"\r\n- 🔎 **Code Discovery**: \"Locate all database migration files and summarize changes\"\r\n\r\n## Why This Is SUPER IMPORTANT\r\n\r\n**Before Subagents:**\r\n```\r\nYour Chat:\r\n[1000 tokens of research]\r\n[500 tokens of API docs]\r\n[800 tokens of code analysis]\r\n[Your actual question]\r\n❌ Context limit reached!\r\n```\r\n\r\n**With Subagents:**\r\n```\r\nYour Chat:\r\n[Your actual question]\r\nSubagent Result: [Clean, summarized findings]\r\n✅ Context optimized!\r\n```\r\n\r\n## The Power of Delegation\r\n\r\nThink of subagents as **specialist consultants** - they do the deep dive research and come back with concise answers, leaving your main conversation focused on the actual problem you're solving.\r\n\r\n**Pro Tip**: Combine subagents with the Plan Agent for maximum efficiency - let subagents gather context while the Plan Agent structures your implementation approach!\r\n\r\n**Availability**: VS Code Insiders only (as of version 1.105)\r\n\r\nLearn more: [Subagents Documentation](https://code.visualstudio.com/docs/copilot/chat/chat-sessions#_subagents)"
    },
    {
      "title": "🆕 Managing All Your Agent Work: The Agent Sessions Hub",
      "description": "# 🆕 Agent Sessions View - Your Agentic Work Command Center\r\n\r\n**New in VS Code 1.105**: The **Agent Sessions View** provides a unified hub to manage ALL your AI-powered work across different platforms and modes.\r\n\r\n## What Is the Agent Sessions View?\r\n\r\nThink of it as **mission control for all your agent work**. It's a centralized location that gives you visibility into:\r\n\r\n### 🏠 Local Work\r\n- Your local chat conversations\r\n- In-editor AI interactions\r\n- Active Copilot sessions\r\n\r\n### ☁️ Remote Coding Agents\r\n- **GitHub Copilot Coding Agent** - Cloud-based implementation tasks\r\n- **GitHub Copilot CLI** - Terminal-based AI assistance\r\n- **OpenAI Codex** - Advanced coding models (with Copilot Pro+ subscription)\r\n\r\n## Key Features\r\n\r\n### 📊 Session Management\r\n- **Track Progress**: See status of all active agent sessions\r\n- **Context Menus**: Quick actions for each session\r\n- **Rich Descriptions**: Detailed context for what each agent is working on\r\n- **Status Bar Tracking**: Monitor multiple agents simultaneously\r\n\r\n### ⚡ Quick Actions\r\n- **Create New Sessions**: Use the \"+\" button in the view header\r\n- **Resume Sessions**: Pick up where you left off on any agent task\r\n- **Delegate Work**: Move tasks between local and remote agents\r\n- **Manage Long-Running Tasks**: Perfect for background compilation, testing, or analysis\r\n\r\n## Integration Highlights\r\n\r\n### GitHub Copilot CLI\r\n- Kick off and resume CLI sessions directly from the view\r\n- Use `/delegate` in a CLI chat to hand off work to the cloud coding agent\r\n- Attach context from your editor just like in regular chat\r\n- Integrated terminal support for CLI workflows\r\n\r\n### OpenAI Codex\r\n- Powered by your existing Copilot subscription (Pro+)\r\n- Automatic authentication - no additional setup needed\r\n- Manage both Copilot and Codex sessions from one interface\r\n\r\n## Configuring the View\r\n\r\n**Setting**: `chat.agentSessionsViewLocation`\r\n\r\nChoose where the Agent Sessions view appears in your VS Code layout.\r\n\r\n## Typical Workflow\r\n\r\n1. **Plan Locally**: Use local chat to discuss and plan a feature\r\n2. **Delegate to Remote Agent**: Click \"Delegate to coding agent\" button\r\n3. **Track in Sessions View**: Monitor progress while you work on other tasks\r\n4. **Review Results**: Agent creates PR with implementation\r\n5. **Continue Conversation**: Resume discussion with all context preserved\r\n\r\n## Why This Matters\r\n\r\n**Before**: Juggling multiple AI tools meant:\r\n- ❌ Lost context when switching between tools\r\n- ❌ No visibility into what remote agents are doing\r\n- ❌ Manual tracking of multiple conversations\r\n\r\n**Now**: The Agent Sessions Hub gives you:\r\n- ✅ Unified view of all AI work\r\n- ✅ Seamless transitions between local and remote\r\n- ✅ Full context preservation\r\n- ✅ Better productivity with parallel agent tasks\r\n\r\n## Summary: The Complete Agent Ecosystem\r\n\r\nYou've now learned about:\r\n1. **@plan Agent** - Strategic planning\r\n2. **Subagents** - Focused research and analysis\r\n3. **Agent Sessions View** - Managing it all\r\n\r\nTogether, these tools create a **powerful agentic workflow** where you orchestrate multiple AI assistants working on different aspects of your project simultaneously!\r\n\r\n**Pro Tip**: Use the Agent Sessions View to delegate long-running tasks (like running comprehensive tests or generating documentation) while you continue coding locally.\r\n\r\n**Availability**: Available in both VS Code Stable and Insiders (features rolling out gradually)"
    },
    {
      "title": "Create a Custom Chat Mode: PRD builder",
      "description": "Let's set up our own custom GitHub Copilot Chat Mode to accelerate creation of Product Requirements Documents (PRDs).\n\n**Goal**: Create a mode named **PRD builder** that loads the persona instructions so you can quickly draft structured PRDs from short prompts.\n\n### Steps\n1. Open the Copilot Chat panel (Ctrl + Alt + I).\n1. Click the mode dropdown (where you pick *Ask* / *Agent*). You probably noticed there are already two custom modes, let's create our own by selecting **Configure modes** (see screenshot below).\n\n    ![Configure Modes](./assets/ConfigureModes.png)\n\n1. In the configuration UI, click **Create a new custom mode**.\n\n    ![Create Mode](./assets/Create a new custom mode.png)\n\n1. Let's use the User level scope to share this across projects instead of being project specific\n\n    ![User Data Folder](./assets/UserDataFolder.png)    \n        \n1. Name it exactly: `PRD builder`.\n1. Open this file `PRD-Builder-Persona.md` ([link](./personas/PRD-Builder-Persona.md)) and copy its entire contents into the new mode's definition/instructions text area.\n1. (Optional) Pick an emoji/icon to make it stand out (🧱, 📄, 🚀).\n1. Save the mode.\n\nCongratulations, you've created a custom mode.\n\n\n### What This Gives You\n- Consistent PRD structure (intro, goals, user stories, requirements, non-goals, metrics)\n- Automatic reminder to ask clarifying questions first\n- Faster onboarding for teammates who can reuse the same mode\n\n### Pro Tips\n- You can store multiple personas (e.g., *Test Plan Builder*, *API Spec Writer*) the same way.\n- Version your persona files in Git so the team can improve them collaboratively.\n- If you update the persona text here, re-open the mode config and re-paste to sync.\n\nWhen you're done, try giving it a *very short* feature idea and see how it first asks you clarifying questions (that's by design!).\n\nGive it a spin—your future specs will thank you. ✨"
    },
    {
      "title": "Chat Mode Handoffs: Orchestrating Multi-Step Workflows",
      "description": "**Handoffs** are a powerful feature that enable you to create guided, sequential workflows that transition between different chat modes with suggested next steps.\n\n### What Are Handoffs?\nHandoffs appear as interactive buttons after a chat response completes, allowing users to seamlessly move to the next mode with:\n- Relevant context preserved from the previous step\n- A pre-filled prompt tailored to the next workflow stage\n- Optional auto-submission for fully automated flows\n\n### The Power of Orchestration\nWe've built a complete workflow for feature development:\n\n1. **PRD Builder Mode** - Start with a brief feature idea\n   - AI asks clarifying questions\n   - Creates a detailed Product Requirements Document\n   - ↓ *Handoff button: \"Generate Tasks\"*\n\n2. **PRD to Tasks Mode** - Transform the PRD into actionable tasks\n   - Analyzes functional requirements\n   - Generates high-level parent tasks\n   - Breaks down into detailed sub-tasks\n   - ↓ *Handoff button: \"Process Tasks\"*\n\n3. **Process Tasks Mode** - Execute the implementation\n   - Helps implement each task step-by-step\n   - Provides code generation and guidance\n   - Validates implementation against PRD\n\n### Why This Matters\n- **No Context Loss** - Information flows seamlessly between modes\n- **Guided Experience** - Users follow a proven workflow without jumping between tools\n- **Iterative Refinement** - Each step builds on the previous one\n- **Reduced Cognitive Load** - One-click transitions vs manual copy-paste\n\n### Try It Out\nYou can see this orchestration in action by:\n1. Opening a custom chat mode file (e.g., `PRD-2🎬.chatmode.md`)\n2. Looking at the `handoffs` section in the YAML frontmatter\n3. Notice how each mode defines its next step\n\n**Pro Tip**: You can chain multiple handoffs together to create even longer workflows—imagine: Planning → Design → Implementation → Testing → Documentation!"
    },
    {
      "file": "EasterEggs.md",
